The paper deals with algorithms for creating $\varepsilon$-samples of range spaces defined by halfspaces, which are fundamental objects in computational geometry and machine learning. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of algorithms, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as possible sub-categories. The paper mentions the use of partition trees, which are a popular data structure in computational geometry, and this further supports the inclusion of cs.CG and cs.DS. The paper also discusses the applications of the algorithms in spatial anomaly detection and range counting, which are topics in cs.SC (Computer Science and Society) and cs.LG (Machine Learning), respectively.
